Naive O(n²) Multiplication

Scales very badly: For n=80,000, sequential takes 3.99 seconds; for n=250,000, it jumps to 46.60 seconds (over 11.7 times slower, while size is only ~3.1 times larger).
Parallel version gives excellent performance on large inputs: At n=250,000 with 16 threads, it takes 6.01 seconds; with 32 threads, 6.07 seconds.

Karatsuba Multiplication

Asymptotically much better than naive: At n=1,000,000, sequential Karatsuba (threshold 64) takes 16.73 seconds.
Parallel Karatsuba performs reasonably well: At n=1,000,000 (threshold 256) with 16 threads, it takes 3.04 seconds (vs. 20.11 seconds sequential); with 32 threads, 3.10 seconds.
The base-case threshold is critical:
Threshold = 64: Good on medium sizes (e.g., n=80,000 sequential: 0.66 seconds), but on very large inputs (≥500,000) shows slightly more recursion overhead (n=1,000,000 sequential: 16.73 seconds).
Threshold = 128: Balanced, gives solid performance in your tests (e.g., n=1,000,000 sequential: 20.18 seconds; parallel 16 threads: 3.84 seconds).
Threshold = 256: Best overall, especially for parallel on huge inputs due to optimal balance between recursion and base cases (e.g., n=1,000,000 sequential: 20.11 seconds; parallel 16 threads: 3.04 seconds).
Thresholds below 64 (e.g., 32, as you tested): Too many tiny recursive calls lead to huge overhead, making it slower than naive (specific times not provided, but generally 1.5–2x worse than optimal thresholds).